**Abstract:**
Major essay dated November 4, 1997 titled "God is a proper name" building on 97-OCT-2. Critiques Lonergan's treatment of God as an "It" with an essence in Verbum. Examines Plato and Aristotle on knowledge, then develops extensive analysis of why Aristotle's "practical knowledge" fails as genuine knowledge under his own correspondence theory. Argues practical judgment is not susceptible of truth/falsity and thus not knowledge at all. Includes extensive material on human vs. animal knowledge.

**AI Recommendation:** Major theoretical essay; critical of Aristotelian epistemology. See also 97-OCT-1, 97-OCT-2.

